  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several key ways:\n\n1. International Conventions and Agreements\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n\n2. Standardization of Legal Frameworks\n- Establishing common definitions of money laundering\n- Creating consistent legal standards for detection and prosecution\n- Promoting cross-border cooperation\n\n3. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Treaties enabling information sharing between countries\n- Coordinated investigations of transnational financial crimes\n- Extradition of individuals involved in money laundering\n\n4. Compliance Requirements\n- Banks and financial institutions must follow international standards\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious transaction reporting mechanisms\n\n5. Enforcement Mechanisms\n- International sanctions\n- Asset freezing and seizure\n- Diplomatic and economic pressure\n\n6. Technological Challenges\n- Addressing digital currency and cryptocurrency regulations\n- Developing cross-border digital investigation techniques\n\n7. Jurisdictional Considerations\n- Resolving conflicts between different national legal systems\n- Determining appropriate venue for prosecution\n\nThese intersections create a complex but increasingly coordinated global approach to combating money laundering.",
